  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3588042534" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3588042534" />
    <a title="Antonomasia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6249204-antonomasia"><img alt="Antonomasia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609885936p2/6249204.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3588042534?book_show_action=true">Oct 10, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Antonomasia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Antonomasia" href="/user/show/6249204-antonomasia">Antonomasia</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679734772" href="/book/show/139253.The_House_on_Mango_Street">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Antonomasia by: </span>
      Catching up on Classics group
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=decade-1980s">decade-1980s</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=novella">novella</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=young-adult">young-adult</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=chicago">chicago</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=childrens">childrens</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=2020">2020</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=feminism">feminism</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=hispanosphere">hispanosphere</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=latin-american">latin-american</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6249204-antonomasia?shelf=modern-american-fiction">modern-american-fiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3588042534" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16689739392197883945">Sometimes it looks like a person just read a book at the wrong age. (cf. All those underwhelmed reviews following first-time reads of <i>The Secret History</i> by over-30s.) But I&apos;m not sure there&apos;s a time when I would have really loved <i>The House on Mango Street</i>, one of those modern classics that&apos;s huge in the USA, including on their school curriculum - and therefore on GR - but which is not as well-known in the UK. I read it mostly to help finish a reading challenge, because it&apos;s very short, but I was</span>
  <span id="freeText16689739392197883945" style="display:none">Sometimes it looks like a person just read a book at the wrong age. (cf. All those underwhelmed reviews following first-time reads of <i>The Secret History</i> by over-30s.) But I'm not sure there's a time when I would have really loved <i>The House on Mango Street</i>, one of those modern classics that's huge in the USA, including on their school curriculum - and therefore on GR - but which is not as well-known in the UK. I read it mostly to help finish a reading challenge, because it's very short, but I was also curious, because in the group hosting said challenge, a lot of members love this book.<br /><br />I can at least appreciate Cisneros' project better in middle age, even if I only enjoyed the book moderately. <br /><br /><i>Mango Street</i> seems to be a story for secondary-school age readers (don't ask me how it fits with the whole American middle-school thing - but to me it seems right to find it in the library when starting secondary school), due to the latter half's non-graphic inclusion of themes of puberty and the protagonist's and her friends' dodgy interactions with boys and men. However the vocabulary is - deliberately - simpler than in 20th century children's books I was reading at eight or nine, e.g. Arthur Ransome, Susan Cooper. At secondary school age, I would have seen <i>Mango Street</i> was not for me, and because I was held back by school lessons and didn't know other kids at the same level, it would have annoyed me. (IME, intellectual isolation is a major breeding ground for intellectual snobbery.) But there were lots of other books that suited me better, and which took longer to read, so there was no need to waste much time dwelling on ones like this when I encountered books them. They were meant for other people, kids who had problems like the narrator and her friends and/or who found reading more difficult. But I can't help be hypothetically frustrated at the idea of this book being taught at length to bright US teenagers who need something more complex to keep them interested if they don't love the story. An entire bloody term on <i>For Mice and Men</i> at GCSE was bad enough, never mind this. (Yes, there can be and have been PhDs done on texts like these, but PhD literature students work on texts they like, and often use a lot of theory. That is a very different matter from sitting through two or three hours a week for the best part of three months, going over points that were obvious on a first reading. Books like these do feel threadbare taught at that level of detail compared with a Shakespeare play.)<br /><br />Now, I can see that Cisneros had important aims in writing <i>Mango Street</i>, which I'm very sympathetic to, including (speaking of her past self in the 2009 introduction): "She thinks people who are busy working for a living deserve beautiful little stories, because they don’t have much time and are often tired. She has in mind a book that can be opened at any page and will still make sense to the reader who doesn’t know what came before or comes after."<br /><br />There are times when I need something like that myself. However, the kind of writing found in <i>The House on Mango Street</i> isn't what I want at those times. The ideal thing would be a well-written popular fiction genre novel, but not 400 pages as a lot of them are bloated to these days. (About halfway through <i>Mango Street</i>, I found myself looking up, and doing librarian edits on the UK <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/list/show/92494.Quick_Reads_Programme" rel="nofollow noopener">Quick Reads</a> series, books of circa 100 pages designed for adult literacy, language learners, or just as it says, 'quick reads' - as some of those might be the answer for those times.) [ETA a couple of weeks later: having just read one of the Quick Reads novellas,<a href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3591766650" rel="nofollow noopener">Looking for Captain Poldark</a> by Rowan Coleman, the prose was never noticeably, jarringly simplistic the way it was in <i>Mango Street</i>.]<br /><br />I want to hear a bit about what happens next - not always abrupt ending after abrupt ending to vignettes, as in the repetitive rhythm here; or the try-hard humourless metaphors; and hints of that tedious structural atmosphere of modern literary short stories I call 'brittleness'. It looks like Iowa Writers' workshop did indeed rub off on the author. Or is it just a style of the times? There's the child-narrator thing, which I don't usually like unless they're precocious brats (and with what seems to me like overegged naivety but I'm not the target audience so I'm probably wrong about that). And the occasional slightly-experimental slightly-stream-of-consciousness thing, which I quite like but would have preferred with more humour. I was really disappointed to read in the introduction that the author went to Iowa, but had hoped that her sense of being an outsider would make this book something more different than it turned out to be from contemporary creative-writing course fiction. (And she studied poetry at Iowa, not fiction - though that shows in the use of vignettes. The writing mostly isn't poetic enough to call it 'poetic prose', but many of the vignettes are essentially poems in prose.) <br /><br />However, if Cisneros hadn't gone to Iowa, maybe she wouldn't have got published, or <i>Mango Street</i> wouldn't have got such a big publisher and she wouldn't have broken ground for the subsequent generations of US Latina writers. Her 1993 introduction talks about how, when she was growing up, she had hardly encountered any books about working-class kids like herself. But - although Britain perhaps had a stronger existing tradition because of the kitchen-sink drama trend of the 1950s and 60s - Cisneros publishing <i>Mango Street</i> in 1983/4 no doubt helped influence authors in the following years to write more about them. Therefore, reading this, I could think that, back in the 90s, there were already quite a lot of proto-YA novels about poorer kids and teenagers, so it didn't seem so unusual. So it doesn't matter if someone like me didn't enjoy it that much, it's not the point of the book. <br /><br />Just as <i>Mango Street</i> feels like home to some readers, it reminds me of where I didn't fit in. Of the stage where I decided I needed to understand 'ordinary life' a bit better and hung out with some girls from a less-well-off area near one of their houses. It was interesting to see the place, and to talk to people who actually read Mills and Boon (like her gran). But I have never been so bored in my life as in those afternoons sitting on walls trying to think of random things to say about or to people going past, in words that fitted in in that area, whilst numb and cold about the arse and legs. I didn't know about Aspergers then. And as in some other working-class feminist literature from the 1980s (cf <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/945955" rel="nofollow noopener">My Mother Said I Never Should</a> by Charlotte Keatley), there are scenes with skipping rhymes. These are meant to connect with readers. But I couldn't skip, and I always associated the rhymes with bitchiness, and other girl-group behaviours that were somewhat mystifying but mostly just boring to me.<br /><br />There was a point when some of the feminism in <i>Mango Street</i> might have seemed rather 70s and 80s, a bit sledgehammer, but now it seems once again to chime with the cultural mood, highlighting problems like the sleazy men staring at preteen girls in high-heels, or US states that allowed child marriage.<br /><br />It was the local and cultural detail that interested me most in <i>Mango Street</i>: in the 2009 introduction, Cisneros talking about writing in Chicago and in or near neighbourhoods Nelson Algren and Saul Bellow had frequented. How Esperanza felt about her name and its meanings in Spanish and English. (Oscar Wilde's mum, referred to as Speranza in Richard Ellman's Wilde biography, has been my first association with the name/word since my teens, and is of course never mentioned - this is a different world.) The way when the kids thought of clutches of names that seemed to be for imaginary people, they were a mixture of Spanish and English - which seemed to reflect their greater closeness to their heritage culture. I sometimes used to make up names for characters which used Polish sounds and spelling (and mind when entirely English teachers didn't understand how they were supposed to be pronounced) but I don't think I ever used actual Polish names. <br /><br />Previously, I was keen to read <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/32957" rel="nofollow noopener">Caramelo</a>, Cisneros novel for adults; I'm still very interested in it for the story and the Spanish/Mexican but a little more wary of the tone as I see echoes of <i>Mango Street</i>'s style in the first few pages.<br /><br />Nevertheless, at crucial moments, <i>Mango Street</i> manages to be moving without being cloying - an important quality - including in the last few scenes which show how Esperanza / Cisneros partly escapes the place where she grew up, but also returns, metaphorically and/or actually, to help support others, via the book she has written.<br /><br />10/10/2020</span>
  <a data-text-id="16689739392197883945" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


