<div id="review_1934617436" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1934617436" />
    <a title="Paloma" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5931265-paloma"><img alt="Paloma" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1579496209p2/5931265.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1934617436?book_show_action=true">Mar 07, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Paloma" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Paloma" href="/user/show/5931265-paloma">Paloma</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780679734772" href="/book/show/139253.The_House_on_Mango_Street">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5931265-paloma?shelf=owned">owned</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5931265-paloma?shelf=2018-popsugar-challenge">2018-popsugar-challenge</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5931265-paloma?shelf=literatura-estadounidense">literatura-estadounidense</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5931265-paloma?shelf=reading-challenge-2018">reading-challenge-2018</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5931265-paloma?shelf=reviewed-rese%C3%B1ados">reviewed-reseñados</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1934617436" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17947755300294210837">
  <i>“You can never have too much sky. You can fall asleep and wake up drunk on sky and sky can keep you safe when you are sad. Here, there is too much sadness and not enough sky. Butterflies too are few and so are flowers and more things that are beautiful. Still, we take what we can get and make the best of it.&quot; </i>
<br/><br/><b>Review in English | Reseña en español (breve)</b><br/><br/>This book was a beautiful surprise -exquisite, delicate, hard- a quiet gem that is not there for exhibit but if one is lucky enough to find </span>
  <span id="freeText17947755300294210837" style="display:none">
  <i>“You can never have too much sky. You can fall asleep and wake up drunk on sky and sky can keep you safe when you are sad. Here, there is too much sadness and not enough sky. Butterflies too are few and so are flowers and more things that are beautiful. Still, we take what we can get and make the best of it." </i>
<br /><br /><b>Review in English | Reseña en español (breve)</b><br /><br />This book was a beautiful surprise -exquisite, delicate, hard- a quiet gem that is not there for exhibit but if one is lucky enough to find it, it will mesmerize you. I say this because as Mexican, one is not likely to read or feel attracted to Chicano literature. I am speaking entirely from my experience and as such, I had never approached this literature three reasons: first, it is difficult to understand the culture of those who, sharing our roots, move away, adopt the American way of life and slowly begin forgetting our traditions, including how to speak Spanish; second, it is always difficult to grasp the scope and meaning of "Spanglish"; and third, as with many others, it has become a different cultural community -regardless of our shared past. <br /><br />I recall that many, many years ago, during my high school years, I had this small book whose title was <i>You have seen our faces</i>. This was one of the books for my English class and it included chapters of different books but whose common theme was identity in the U.S. When last week I started reading The House in Mango Street, I knew I had already heard about Esperanza, the girl whose name means hope in English but in Spanish it means <i>too many letters, sadness, waiting</i>. I was too young when I first read this fragment but I remember vividly that I didn't like it. I could not feel empathy with a girl of Mexican roots who felt lonely in a different country. Her loneliness seemed unnatural and mostly (now that I look back), scary. <br /><br />It would take me 15 years to meet again with this book. The person I am now is different in a lot of ways from my teenage years. Most likely age is the factor that has helped go through this book. Esperanza's voice -the main character of this small novel- does not feel alien anymore: it is, as with many other characters of the best literature, a voice with which we can identify ourselves.<br /><br />This is not a long novel and in fact, each chapter has barely 3 pages. That is how we learn from the hopes, dreams and fears of a young teenage girl living in Chicago, who longs for a place to truly call home, with parents moving from one place to another, and friends and family coming and going. <br /><br />This is also not a book with great actions or adventures, the tone is slow yet powerful -I couldn't believe how short sentences could have a such a strong and lasting impact in one's mind. Though my knowledge in U.S. literature is not that much, I think that it was Cisnero's writing that started a new trend in books: short chapters, written in first perosn, and brief sentences to keep the reader interested. However, it must be said that while I think that there has been an abuse of this way of writting in contemporary fiction, this was not the case with Cisneros. Maybe because she was the first, and because her interest was not to sell books?<br /><br />Anyway -each "vignette", as I think the small chapters of this book have been defined, show the reader a precise image of the world of this girl, her family, her sister, and her friends. It is not only her looking for an identity but also every one living in Mango Street: Marin, the girl from Puerto Rico; Ruthie, the daughter of the owner of one of the buildings, her aunt Lupe. It is a tough story about growing up, of trying to make sense of what sourrounds us of childhood. In the end, we might move from a house, from a city, but the places where we grew, will always be a part of us. And we'll always return there, either in person or in mind. <br /><br />This is a book full of nostalgia, of longing. I think also this might not be a book for everyone -for a second I thought this is the type of story I could have disliked, because of the writing style; luckily, this was not the case. Though I did not grew in a environment such as Esperanza's, her thoughts and words touched me deeply and I did not need a throughly constructed background to understand her. The simplicity with which we learn from her life is enough, perfect: <br /><br />
  <i>“…then it is I looked at trees. When there is nothing left to look at on this street. Four who grew despite concrete. Four who reach and do not forget to reach. Four whose only reason is to be and to be"</i>
.<br /><br />Perhaps it helped a lot the wonderful introduction by Cisneros included in this edition. In it, the author tells as about herself when writing this book, of her own fears and doubts about becoming a writer, about learning from other authors, about her then present and the hopes of the futures. What I kept the most, is when Cisneros says that for her:<br /><br /><i>"stories are about beauty. Beauty that is there to be admired by anyone, like a heard of clouds grazing overhead (...) people who are busy working for a living deserve beautiful little stories, because they don’t have that much time and are often tired"</i>. <br /><br />And I couldn't agree more with one of my very own personal beliefs: above all, novels or fiction at least, should be about beauty -not in the sense of happy endings but of the narrative, of the images they create on us, of the emotions they create in our souls. And <i>The House on Mango Street</i> definitely achieves this. <br /><br />_______________________<br /><br />La reseña en español es breve porque hay libros que <i>siento más</i> en su idioma original y por ello, entonces me parece complicado transmitir esos sentimientos en otro idioma. Este ha sido el caso con esta pequeña novela de Sandra Cisneros. Y a pesar que había algunos elementos presentes, los cuales me han hecho odiar otros libros, este no ha sido el caso. De hecho, he quedado honestamente sorprendida, maravillada con la historia de <i>The House on Mango Street</i> y la historia de Esperanza, una adolescente que anhela una casa propia, una vida distinta, algo afuera de la monotonía. A través de sus ojos vamos descubriendo las preocupaciones de una comunidad -en este caso, la latina y chicana en EUA- y el deseo común de salir, de cambiar. ¿A dónde o cómo? Es una buena pregunta que en todo caso no se resuelve del todo en el libro. Pero eso no es lo importante. Esta historia me gustó porque en pocos capítulos, enunciados concretos, se descubren mundos y sentimientos profundos, mágicos. La historia de una chica boricua que baila y baila esperando que algo cambie; una mujer que perdió la razón cuando antes escribía libros infantiles, mujeres que esperan un cambio, sentadas frente a ventanas. Esperanza no es así, y si vida cambiará, aunque no lo lleguemos a ver. Pero el final o el futuro no es lo relevante: lo es la convicción, el anhelo, la promesa de un futuro mejor. <br /><br />No sé si en español este libro tendrá un impacto semejante en el lector -algo que admiro y envidio del inglés es que con enunciados muy sencillos se pueden crear frases bellas, que resuenan en nuestra mente y alma de manera profunda. Esta edición contiene una introducción por la propia autora, la cual es muy valiosa para entender este libro. Cisneros indica que, para ella las historias:<br /><br />
  <i>"deben ser sobre la belleza. La belleza que está presente para ser admirada por todos, como un rebaño de nubes que pastan sobre nuestras cabezas (...) la gente que está ocupada trabajando para poder vivir merece historias bellas y pequeñas, porque no tienen mucho tiempo para leer y con frecuencia están cansadas..."</i>
<br /><br />Yo comparto esa opinión -las historias, por lo menos el arte de la ficción, deben ser bellas, y con ello no me refiero a que haya finales felices, sino en los mundos que crean a través de la narrativa, y a los cuales escapamos y en los sentimientos (buenos o malos) que crean en nuestra alma. Y este libro, sin duda lo logra.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17947755300294210837" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


